sions J.J. Engel's Herr Lorenz Stark and the Pathognomy of Style -- tHow to Study Emotion Effects in Literature Written Emotions in Edgar Allan Poe's "The Fall of the House of Usher" -- tPosthuman Nostalgia? Re-Evaluating Human Emotions in Michel Houellebecq's La possibilité d'une île .. -- tWriting Wounds -- tWriting Disgust, Writing Realities The Complexity of Negative Emotions in Émile Zola's Nana -- tBreaking the Ice, Freezing the Laughter Authorial Empathy, Reader Response, and the Kafkaesque Poetics of Guilt and Shame -- tHiding One's Feelings 'Emotionless' Rhetoric in Raul Hilberg's The Destruction of the European Jews and Peter Weiss's Die Ermittlung -- tLove under Threat The Emotional Valences of the Twilight Saga -- tAUTHORS0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aAfter a long period of neglect, emotions have become an important topic within literary studies. This collection of essays stresses the complex link between aesthetic and non-aesthetic emotional components and discusses emotional patterns by focusing on the practice of writing as well as on the impact of such patterns on receptive processes. Readers interested in the topic will be presented with a concept of aesthetic emotions as formative both within the writing and the reading process. Essays, ranging in focus from the beginning of modern drama to digital formats and theoretical questions, examine examples from English, German, French, Russian and American literature. Contributors include Angela Locatelli, Vera Nünning, and Gesine Lenore Schiewer.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched - KU Select 2017: Frontlist Collection  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page